The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, April 05, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, April 4: Videsh Sanchar Nigam Ltd, in a bid to consolidate its presence in the national long-distance (NLD) segment, has embarked on an ambitious target of setting up a total NLD leg of 25,000 km in the country by March 2006. The NLD plans are part of the companys overall strategies of laying fibre-optic cable in areas which are essential, even as the stress is not to create over capacities in any of the legs, VSNL sources said. Videsh Sanchar already has a 6,000-km-long cable network stretching from Jalandhar in Punjab to Ernakulam in Kerala, covering around 105 cities.																								 Calcutta, April 4: Vizag Steel has registered a record turnover of Rs 6,174 crore in 2003-04, up 22 per cent over the previous fiscal. It also reported the highest-ever net profit of Rs 1,521 crore.																								 New Delhi, April 4: The government is not likely to divest its stake in MMTC, Indias largest trading house until the privatisation of State Trading Corporation is completed, said S. D. Kapoor, MMTCs chairman and managing director.																								 New Delhi, April 4: The Association of Mutual Funds of India (Amfi) has expressed concern over some funds tendency to inflate asset size, especially during the end of a month. Amfi has asked them to publish the average size daily, said A. P. Kurian, Amfi chairman.																								 Mumbai, April 4: The Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) has rejected a plea by the promoters of Gujarat Ambuja Exports to exempt them from making an open offer to company shareholders while acquiring an additional stake and voting rights in the firm.
